The easiest way to think about it is this:

What you’ve designed is not a specific product.
It’s a coordination architecture.

It organizes:
	•	ideas
	•	tools
	•	problems
	•	solutions
	•	people
	•	AI systems

Any domain where those things exist can use the same structure.

Below are the most natural application domains and what the system would actually do in each.

⸻

1. Scientific Research

One of the strongest fits.

Current problem in research:
	•	ideas scattered across papers
	•	duplication of work
	•	hard to find methods that transfer between fields

Pantheon-style system:

Artifacts:
	•	papers
	•	datasets
	•	methods
	•	proofs
	•	experimental workflows

Markets:
	•	physics
	•	biology
	•	AI
	•	mathematics
	•	climate science

Atlas use:
	•	detect connections between fields
	•	identify missing experiments
	•	show when a method in one field solves a problem in another

Example:

Graph Laplacian methods (math)
      ↓
Network diffusion (biology)
      ↓
Recommendation systems (AI)

The Atlas reveals these bridges.

